# TideReport Project Rules

This project is a **Fish shell** plugin for [Tide][] that adds configurable prompt items (weather, moon, tide, GitHub). All work assumes **Fish** and **TideReport**; no Bash or other shells.

## Never Delay the Prompt

**Critical:** Prompt items must **never** block or delay the prompt. Prefer showing no data or stale data over any delay.

- Fetch data in the **background** (e.g. `&` at end of fetch command). Never await network or slow I/O on the main prompt path.
- Use **file-based or variable-based cache**. On prompt run: read cache only; if cache is missing or expired, show the configured "unavailable" text and trigger a background refresh.
- Two timers: **refresh** (show stale data, refresh in background) and **expire** (show unavailable, refresh in background). Never block while fetching.

## Fish Shell Only â€” No Bashisms

- Use Fish syntax and builtins only. No `[[ ]]`, `$(( ))`, `&>/dev/null`, or Bash-specific constructs.
- Prefer: `test` / `string` / `math` / `command`; `set -l` for locals; `set -q var || set -U var value` for optional universal defaults; `^/dev/null` or redirects like `2>/dev/null` where needed.
- Give functions a `--description` for help. Use `--argument-names` for explicit arguments where it helps clarity.

## Fish `set_color` â€” Correct usage

Fishâ€™s `set_color` sets terminal colors. **Argument order depends on whether `-b` is first** and is easy to get wrong.

- **When `-b` / `--background` comes first:** `set_color -b BACKGROUND FOREGROUND`  
  Example: `set_color -b white red` â†’ red text on white background. So **suffix/prefix** (black bg, segment color as fg) must be: `set_color -b black $tide_github_bg_color`.
- **When foreground is specified first:** `set_color FOREGROUND -b BACKGROUND`  
  Example: `set_color white -b blue` â†’ white text on blue background.
- **Do not mix the two forms:** Use one or the other consistently. For â€śblack background, segment color as textâ€ť always use `set_color -b black $segment_bg_color` (option first).
- **Reference:** Tideâ€™s install wizard uses `set_color $prev_bg_color -b normal` for suffix (foreground first; see `~/.config/fish/functions/tide/configure/functions/_fake_tide_prompt.fish`). Our wizard uses black background, so we use `set_color -b black $segment_bg_color`.

## Naming Conventions

Follow existing TideReport and Tide patterns:

| Kind | Pattern | Example |
|------|---------|--------|
| Tide prompt item (entry point) | `_tide_item_<name>` | `_tide_item_weather`, `_tide_item_moon` |
| Shared / public helper | `_tide_report_<name>` | `_tide_report_handle_async_weather` |
| Private / parser helper | `__tide_report_<name>` | `__tide_report_parse_weather`, `__tide_report_get_moon_emoji` |
| Config (plugin) | `tide_report_<module>_<option>` | `tide_report_weather_format`, `tide_report_moon_expire_seconds` |
| Config (Tide item colors) | `tide_<item>_color`, `tide_<item>_bg_color` | `tide_weather_color`, `tide_moon_bg_color` |

When adding a new prompt item, register it in `conf.d/tide_report.fish` (defaults, install/uninstall item lists) and in README (Available Prompt Sections, Usage, and any new config tables).

## New Prompt Items

New items should be consistent with the current approach:

- Add `functions/_tide_item_<name>.fish` that Tide will autoload.
- Entry point: `_tide_item_<name>` that sets locals (cache path, refresh/expire, unavailable text/color), calls a cache/async helper if applicable, then a parser that uses `_tide_print_item <name> ...` for output.
- Reuse shared async behavior where possible (e.g. `_tide_report_handle_async_weather` for weather, `_tide_report_handle_async_moon` for moon). For other APIs, follow the same pattern: read cache â†’ if invalid show unavailable + background fetch; if valid parse and print.
- Add defaults in `conf.d/tide_report.fish` with `set -q var || set -U var value`. Include the new item name in the uninstall logic that strips items from `tide_left_prompt_items` / `tide_right_prompt_items`.

## Dependencies

- **jq** and **curl** are in use; adding them is acceptable when needed for new features.
- Be **reluctant to add new dependencies**. Prefer Fish builtins and existing tools. Justify any new dependency.

## Fisher install event contract

- The installer runs when **Fisher** emits the event after sourcing our `conf.d` file. Fisher derives the event name from the **conf.d filename** (basename without `.fish`): for `conf.d/tide_report.fish` it emits `tide_report_install` (or `tide_report_update` on update, `tide_report_uninstall` on remove). Follow the [Fisher docs](https://github.com/jorgebucaran/fisher#creating-a-plugin) pattern (e.g. flipper.fish â†’ flipper_install).
- Our handlers are `_tide_report_install` / `_tide_report_update` / `_tide_report_uninstall` with `--on-event tide_report_install` / `tide_report_update` / `tide_report_uninstall`. Do **not** rely on `status current-command` or `$argv` to trigger the installer.
- If events do not run: Fish may lazy-load `--on-event` handlers (fish-shell/fish-shell#2667, #845). To see what Fisher actually emits, add a temporary `emit` wrapper in config.fish that logs to a file (e.g. `/tmp/tide_report_emit.log`) then calls `builtin emit $argv`; run `fisher install` and inspect the log. If the event name matches but the handler never runs, we may need to invoke the handler once at the end of conf.d so it is registered before Fisherâ€™s emit.
- If the conf.d filename is renamed, the event name changes and the handlerâ€™s `--on-event` must be updated to match.

## Documentation and Configuration

- **README.md** must stay in sync with code: every config variable must be documented (name, description, default). Update the relevant module section and tables when adding or changing options.
- Instructions are for **layman users** on a public GitHub repo: clear, step-by-step, and descriptive. Assume Fisher + Tide are installed per their docs.

## Versioned User Agent

- The **single source of truth** for the plugin version is `_tide_report_version` in `conf.d/tide_report.fish`. The user agent sent to APIs is derived from it (`tide-report/$_tide_report_version`).
- When cutting a new release (e.g. `v1.5`), update `_tide_report_version` to match (e.g. set to `1.5`). No separate user-agent edit is needed.
- Do not ship a new release without bumping this value; it is used for display (e.g. install message) and for external service telemetry/debugging.

## Testing

- This repo has an automated **Fishtape** test suite. After substantive changes, prefer running the VS Code `Test` task or `fish scripts/run_tests_isolated.fish` from the repo root.
- The isolated runner exists so tests that use `set -U` do not modify the developer's real Fish universal variables. Preserve that isolation when changing test flow.
- GitHub Actions runs the suite on **Ubuntu** and **macOS** on pushes and pull requests. Keep changes compatible with both GNU and BSD `date` behavior.
- A supported pre-push gated check-in hook exists at `scripts/pre-push`; when relevant, keep it aligned with the current test entrypoint.
- Do not introduce a different test framework unless the user asks.

